article.description:
Janeth Arcain scored the winning basket with 2.7 seconds remaining Thursday night as the Houston Comets beat the
Indiana Fever 65-63 for their sixth straight victory.
article.headline: Swoopes comes alive in second half
article.linkText: Arcain bucket with 2.7 left gives Comets 6th straight win
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The game was on the line and Houston's
Sheryl Swoopes, the leading vote-getter for this week's WNBA
All-Star game, decided to be a playmaker.

Instead of shooting, she passed the ball to Janeth Arcain, who
hit the game-winning shot with 2.7 seconds remaining as the Houston
Comets beat the Indiana Fever 65-63 Thursday night. It was
Houston's sixth straight victory.

"I felt they were going to be expecting me to do something with
the ball," Swoopes said. "Janeth Arcain, not many people know
about her and know what she is capable of doing. It didn't surprise
me that she hit the shot. ... She's hit so many game-winners."

The 12-footer gave Arcain a season-high 16 points. She scored
both of Houston's baskets in the final 36 seconds, taking a pass
from Swoopes and hitting a jumper each time. Swoopes scored all 14
of her points in the second half for Houston (10-5).

"It felt very natural for me to have the ball," Arcain said.
"Teams always play Sheryl tough. The plan was for me to hold the
ball until 8 to 10 seconds were left. I just did my move and I had
the confidence. They were playing Sheryl so tough."

Swoopes, who came into the game as the league's second-leading
scorer with an 18.3 average, missed her only two shots from field
in the first half and was scoreless until she hit a 3-pointer with
12:17 left in the game. She scored 12 of Houston's next 14 points.

"The way they were defending me all night long, it was a lot
easier for them to take the ball away from me and then have it
brought back to me," she said of her assists on the final two
baskets. "I thought we did a great job of executing the play."

Tamika Catchings led Indiana with 26 points, her second-highest
total of the season. Her 22-footer at the buzzer bounced off the
rim to preserve Houston's victory.

The Fever were playing their first game since June 28 and it
showed in the first half as Indiana fell behind by as many as 10
points.

"I think it was the long break," Catchings said. "It was an
adjustment coming back."

"Our team showed a lot of character. This was a big win for
us," said Houston coach Van Chancellor, whose team moved within a
half-game of first-place Sacramento in the Western Conference.
"What a shot by Janeth. The good news was Sheryl suggested the
play. You've got a superstar who suggested we run a play for Arcain
because she was red hot."

Indiana (8-6) made the game close, shooting 63.6 percent in the
second half and taking its first lead at 57-56 with 5:44 to go.
Houston regained the lead on two free throws by Swoopes, but Tully
Bevilaqua's 3-pointer gave Indiana a 59-57 advantage with about
five minutes remaining.

The Fever followed that with a three-minute scoreless drought
and needed two free throws by Catchings to tie it at 61 with two
minutes left.

After Arcain scored, Catchings tied the game for the final time
at 63 with 27.7 seconds to go. Houston called a timeout and then
let the clock run down until Arcain's game-winning turnaround
jumper.

Houston scored the game's first six points and led the rest of
the first half by as many as 10 points.

The Comets hit eight of their first 13 shots and led 31-21
before a 3-pointer by Kelly Miller and a steal and layup by
Catchings started the Fever's comeback.
